WEBVTT

00:01.160 --> 00:03.359
On this episode of MythBusters,

00:03.360 --> 00:04.859
buckle up for thrills,

00:04.860 --> 00:08.959
spills and chills.

00:08.960 --> 00:10.469
I can't feel my fingers.

00:10.470 --> 00:15.180
First, Adam and Jamie go all
out for some spy car combat...

00:15.310 --> 00:17.669
Oh I got you, oh yeah.
You want some of this?

00:17.670 --> 00:19.910
...testing whether wheels of misfortune...

00:20.435 --> 00:22.435
Ha-ha! That enough for ya?

00:22.490 --> 00:25.749
...and hood-mounted
machine guns really work.

00:25.750 --> 00:28.830
Is this what you want, man?
I can follow you.

00:29.510 --> 00:32.700
Meanwhile, Kari, Grant
and Tory get in a spin...

00:32.725 --> 00:33.925
MythBusters on ice.

00:34.850 --> 00:38.029
...as they find out if a bullet
fired into a frozen lake

00:38.030 --> 00:41.200
can really spin like a top.

00:41.270 --> 00:42.870
See, there is no string here.

00:42.940 --> 00:45.950
It's a story that starts
in San Francisco...

00:46.670 --> 00:48.889
I don't see any spinning bullet.

00:48.890 --> 00:54.120
...but ends in a bitter battle, as the
MythBusters take on Mother Nature.

00:54.960 --> 00:57.160
The next myth is in the Bahamas, right?

00:59.510 --> 01:01.510
Who are the MythBusters?

01:01.790 --> 01:02.800
Adam Savage...

01:02.801 --> 01:03.964
Wow!

01:03.990 --> 01:05.980
...and Jamie Hyneman.

01:06.420 --> 01:08.529
Alright, it's party time.

01:08.530 --> 01:12.569
Between them, more than 30 years
of special effects experience.

01:12.570 --> 01:14.370
Joining them,

01:14.770 --> 01:16.369
Grant Imahara...

01:16.370 --> 01:17.370
For science.

01:18.280 --> 01:19.659
...Kari Byron...

01:19.684 --> 01:20.884
Right tool for the job.

01:21.160 --> 01:23.000
...and Tory Belleci.

01:24.230 --> 01:26.229
They don't just tell the myths.

01:26.230 --> 01:28.560
They put them to the test.

01:28.585 --> 01:32.085
MythBusters 9x07 - Spy Car 2
Original air date May 18, 2011

01:32.110 --> 01:35.579
Sync by YYeTs.net, corrected by atrn97g
www.addic7ed.com

01:35.580 --> 01:38.970
First up, buckle up for
some Spy Car Carnage.

01:40.020 --> 01:41.439
Spy car revenge.

01:41.440 --> 01:42.380
Spy car revenge?

01:42.810 --> 01:45.569
Yeah, the original "Spy Car"
was all about defensive weapons

01:45.570 --> 01:49.329
a spy might have in his car that
could foil someone who's chasing him.

01:49.330 --> 01:52.379
Spy car revenge is about offensive weapons

01:52.380 --> 01:56.229
a chaser would have to
disable a car he's chasing.

01:56.230 --> 01:57.630
What do you have in mind?

01:57.700 --> 01:58.520
I got two things.

01:58.521 --> 02:01.939
The first one: spiky things that
come out of the hubs of their wheels

02:01.940 --> 02:05.089
and tear up their opponents'
cars while they're driving next to them.

02:05.090 --> 02:06.929
Nice. What's the other one?

02:06.930 --> 02:10.889
Guns mounted on the hood of the spy's car.

02:11.390 --> 02:12.979
That is very cool.

02:12.980 --> 02:15.330
- Let's start with the spikes first.
- Okay.

02:15.720 --> 02:18.470
Okay, guys, I'm all oiled up
and ready to go.

02:18.551 --> 02:23.520
In "Spy Car" round one, the
guys evaluated evasion antics,

02:24.840 --> 02:26.540
with mixed success.

02:31.800 --> 02:37.740
But this time, it's out with
escape and in with attack.

02:38.400 --> 02:40.320
But can hood-mounted guns

02:40.800 --> 02:46.220
and hub-mounted wheel spikes
really work first time every time?

02:48.460 --> 02:50.019
So, wheel spikes.

02:50.020 --> 02:52.519
There are tons of movies
that have used that trick.

02:52.520 --> 02:53.418
We can't do all of them.

02:53.419 --> 02:54.280
No, we can't.

02:54.281 --> 02:56.799
I think we should boil
it down and pick two.

02:56.800 --> 02:58.790
Well, there is a classic in "Goldfinger",

02:58.793 --> 03:00.799
it's really simple.
We gotta do that one.

03:00.800 --> 03:03.839
And there is a really
pretty nicely complex one

03:03.840 --> 03:05.168
in "The Green Hornet" I'd like to try out.

03:05.169 --> 03:06.440
Sounds like we've got a plan.

03:06.441 --> 03:07.490
I think we do.

03:08.880 --> 03:11.369
And it's a plan that starts with a delivery

03:11.370 --> 03:13.859
for MythBusters' very own cue.

03:13.860 --> 03:15.820
This car is gonna be our chase car.

03:16.370 --> 03:20.219
When I'm done with it, it's gonna
be a vicious and aggressive car.

03:20.220 --> 03:23.379
In fact, I think I'm going
to call it "Slash",

03:23.380 --> 03:25.310
because that's what it's gonna do.

03:25.660 --> 03:27.789
With Slash sitting pretty,

03:27.790 --> 03:31.320
Jamie begins by building the
first of the two wheel spikes,

03:31.470 --> 03:33.940
the deadly device from "Goldfinger".

03:35.330 --> 03:36.590
It's pretty simple, really.

03:36.591 --> 03:39.289
All it has is a blender-style blade

03:39.290 --> 03:41.580
like this one that I cut
out on the plasma cutter,

03:41.581 --> 03:43.529
attached to the end of the post.

03:43.530 --> 03:46.189
So I will weld on this one here like so,

03:46.190 --> 03:49.870
weld on the hub piece and
then sharpen the blades.

03:50.450 --> 03:53.069
As slashers go, it's certainly simple.

03:53.070 --> 03:54.909
Looks about right to me.

03:54.910 --> 03:57.439
But will the chromoly
steel be strong enough

03:57.440 --> 03:59.310
to not buckle under pressure?

03:59.311 --> 04:00.514
Auch!

04:00.540 --> 04:04.140
Meanwhile, tire slasher two
is anything but basic.

04:04.850 --> 04:07.199
"The Green Hornet" device
is a little more complicated.

04:07.200 --> 04:09.649
It has a bunch of spiky finger-like things

04:09.650 --> 04:12.169
that are welded to a central hub like so.

04:12.170 --> 04:16.410
Now I've mocked all this up in wood,
so that I can get the geometry right.

04:17.010 --> 04:21.149
And then, all I have to do is cut a bunch
of steel pieces out like this,

04:21.149 --> 04:25.090
weld them all together, and I'm done.

04:25.530 --> 04:28.779
In that case, let's cut
to the chase, literally.

04:28.780 --> 04:30.140
You ready to do this?

04:31.050 --> 04:33.040
Are you ready to get slashed up?

04:33.700 --> 04:35.610
Ha ha! You just try and catch me.

04:39.490 --> 04:42.120
Enjoy it while it lasts, buddy.

04:43.520 --> 04:47.789
While Adam spins out for no
reason other than because he can,

04:47.790 --> 04:50.470
Jamie gets on with the odd job in hand,

04:50.840 --> 04:54.099
attaching the "Goldfinger Slinger".

04:54.100 --> 04:55.410
This blade looks pretty nasty.

04:55.411 --> 04:58.159
And I'm positive it will
take out Adam's tire.

04:58.160 --> 05:00.169
But when it comes to meeting
something stronger,

05:00.170 --> 05:05.129
like his wheel or steel parts
of the body, I'm not so sure,

05:05.130 --> 05:09.299
because this is a pretty long lever,
and that means it can get bent.

05:09.300 --> 05:13.299
With that in mind I did make
this out of chromoly steel,

05:13.300 --> 05:15.089
which is very, very strong.

05:15.090 --> 05:18.779
But what it actually does, we're
just gonna have to try and find out.

05:18.780 --> 05:20.740
And to do just that, the
guys are establishing

05:20.741 --> 05:24.559
some very precise rules of engagement.

05:24.560 --> 05:28.369
This story is all about how much damage
Jamie's spikes will do to my car.

05:28.370 --> 05:30.259
I'm not going to avoid him.

05:30.260 --> 05:31.760
I'm going to drive at a constant speed,

05:31.761 --> 05:34.920
while he pulls up and does
as much damage as he can.

05:35.480 --> 05:40.269
So from the green flag, the two cars
will accelerate to 40 miles an hour.

05:40.270 --> 05:41.710
When they hit the red flag,

05:41.711 --> 05:45.139
Jamie will engage the weapon
into the driver side of my car.

05:45.140 --> 05:49.140
He will have 500 yards to inflict
as much damage as he can.

05:50.040 --> 05:53.339
My prediction, I don't think his
Goldfinger spike is gonna do

05:53.340 --> 05:55.559
much more than carve up the side of my car.

05:55.560 --> 05:57.460
I don't think it's gonna take me out.

06:01.680 --> 06:04.219
Dude, nice Goldfinger spikes.

06:04.220 --> 06:06.289
- Pretty nasty, huh?
- Totally.

06:06.290 --> 06:07.310
Are you ready for it?

06:07.311 --> 06:08.720
Absolutely.

06:09.140 --> 06:13.290
With the first spike locked and loaded,
let's get the show on the road.

06:14.070 --> 06:22.470
Okay, Goldfinger spike
in three, two, one...

06:26.300 --> 06:28.069
Both cars accelerate towards

06:28.070 --> 06:30.259
the red flag of the engagement zone.

06:30.260 --> 06:33.440
And once there, the carnage can begin.

06:34.070 --> 06:36.750
Oh, no.

06:37.710 --> 06:41.230
Jamie's first bump tears
through the car door.

06:45.060 --> 06:49.140
The second shreds the tire like a
proverbial knife through butter.

06:53.670 --> 06:58.110
And that loss of traction brings
Adam's car to a slow stop.

06:58.800 --> 07:00.359
You all right there, little buddy?

07:00.360 --> 07:02.009
You totally disabled me.

07:02.010 --> 07:04.719
Meaning that for the
James Bond simple spike,

07:04.720 --> 07:06.990
it's pretty much mission accomplished.

07:07.280 --> 07:11.579
Wow, dude, that is beautiful.

07:11.580 --> 07:13.459
That was crazy effective.

07:13.460 --> 07:16.189
Yeah, it sliced right
through the rear of the car

07:16.190 --> 07:18.499
and went into the tire, no problem.

07:18.500 --> 07:21.470
I have never been in
a purposeful accident...

07:24.320 --> 07:27.609
especially not one where the
person I was driving next to

07:27.610 --> 07:29.489
wanted to cause damage to me.

07:29.490 --> 07:30.960
Oh! That's really scary!

07:31.600 --> 07:33.889
My leg is right on the other side of this.

07:33.890 --> 07:35.140
Check that out.

07:36.030 --> 07:39.839
And it took out this tire magnificently.

07:39.840 --> 07:43.560
I had no idea that this method
would be this effective.

07:44.140 --> 07:47.860
Test one's low tech specs
was a steely success.

07:48.330 --> 07:51.560
But can its more elaborate
counterpart do any better?

07:52.600 --> 07:54.619
Given the success of the Bond spike,

07:54.620 --> 07:57.099
you'd think that this monster
would be a shoo in.

07:57.100 --> 07:58.969
But I'm not so sure.

07:58.970 --> 08:00.759
It's much more complicated;

08:00.760 --> 08:02.190
there's more step to go wrong.

08:02.191 --> 08:04.400
Sometimes size isn't everything.

08:05.690 --> 08:08.030
But will this be one of those times?

08:08.455 --> 08:09.655
Right.

08:10.630 --> 08:12.900
Well, let's roll test two.

08:13.310 --> 08:16.549
Dude, from here, those spikes look sick.

08:16.550 --> 08:19.369
Well, are you ready to feel the touch?

08:19.370 --> 08:20.530
I'm ready. Let's do it.

08:20.531 --> 08:24.890
Okay, "Green Hornet"
in three, two, one...

08:26.230 --> 08:29.210
Like last time, the guys
carefully accelerate,

08:30.280 --> 08:33.110
because they want to know
if the weapon works,

08:33.360 --> 08:35.510
not how easy it is to deploy.

08:36.900 --> 08:39.818
All right, I'm at cruise
control, going at 40.

08:39.820 --> 08:41.020
Here it comes.

08:42.010 --> 08:42.710
Oh, crap.

08:42.840 --> 08:43.900
Oh, crap.

08:44.010 --> 08:45.260
Oh, no.

08:45.360 --> 08:46.640
"Oh, no" is right.

08:46.780 --> 08:49.019
Any hope that this weapon sting would be

08:49.020 --> 08:51.490
harmless is immediately abandoned.

08:53.280 --> 08:54.610
Oh, crap!

08:56.940 --> 08:57.960
Oh, come on.

08:58.090 --> 08:59.530
Come on. Let's have some more. Come on!

08:59.531 --> 09:04.029
Despite Adam's fighting
talk, one bump later,

09:04.030 --> 09:08.210
and his journey is brought
to a premature end.

09:10.840 --> 09:12.220
What did you do to me?

09:12.340 --> 09:15.820
Another successful destruction. Insane!

09:16.510 --> 09:19.719
I think I'm getting a little
better at this as I practice.

09:19.720 --> 09:21.739
Yeah, you took that tire
out pretty handily.

09:21.740 --> 09:24.899
Yeah, I went in right about
here and started to go back

09:24.900 --> 09:26.980
until I hit the tire and heard the bang.

09:28.900 --> 09:30.329
Awesome.

09:30.330 --> 09:33.450
"The Green Hornet" spike made
mincemeat of Adam's car,

09:33.610 --> 09:37.980
opening it up like a sardine can,
and shredding the tire to pieces.

09:39.810 --> 09:41.450
But Jamie's not convinced.

09:41.620 --> 09:44.999
Personally, I think this one is more
showy than anything else, I mean,

09:45.000 --> 09:48.579
It did take out of the tire and
it messed up the side of the car,

09:48.580 --> 09:51.970
but it really didn't do any more
damage than the Bond one did.

09:52.370 --> 09:53.540
Jamie's got a point,

09:53.670 --> 09:57.110
because both wheel spikes did
more or less the same damage.

09:57.750 --> 10:00.020
That felt like I got hit by a power tool!

10:00.130 --> 10:02.850
And both brought Adam to a complete stop.

10:03.010 --> 10:04.400
I lost all power.

10:04.520 --> 10:07.319
But Jamie thinks there
is room for improvement.

10:07.320 --> 10:09.660
Both of our movie spikes work pretty well.
The thing is,

10:09.820 --> 10:13.120
they are really pretty much
just fancy tire poppers,

10:13.280 --> 10:17.040
because who cares if you put scratches
or holes in the sheet metal?

10:17.200 --> 10:18.820
It's not really gonna stop the car.

10:19.560 --> 10:21.680
It makes me wonder though what would.

10:22.380 --> 10:26.890
And that's a thought that should
have Adam very, very afraid.

10:28.150 --> 10:31.719
Still to come, Jamie's
wonder turns to thunder.

10:31.720 --> 10:33.560
You are one sick puppy.

10:34.370 --> 10:36.810
That is messed up.

10:36.930 --> 10:40.900
But next, will a bullet fired
into ice spin like a top?

10:41.050 --> 10:44.020
All right, this is a spinning
bullet at 42 degrees.

10:51.490 --> 10:54.170
Next up, it's time to spin out.

10:56.520 --> 10:57.968
Okay, so our next myth is

10:57.969 --> 11:00.150
based on a video clip that
was sent in by a viewer.

11:00.151 --> 11:01.669
And it's kind of weird.

11:01.670 --> 11:02.858
You still have the video?

11:02.859 --> 11:03.680
I want to see it.

11:03.760 --> 11:05.230
Okay, not like that.

11:05.360 --> 11:07.010
There is a guy on a frozen lake bed

11:07.080 --> 11:10.069
with a bunch of his buddies,
shooting a nine mill into the ice.

11:10.070 --> 11:13.779
And somehow, they get their bullets
to just spin like a top.

11:13.780 --> 11:15.409
Now that sounds like a myth.

11:15.410 --> 11:17.150
That is exactly why we're testing it.

11:18.820 --> 11:23.459
It's no myth that a bullet
fired from a handgun

11:23.460 --> 11:25.700
spins at over 80,000 RPM.

11:26.200 --> 11:32.570
But can a bullet fired into a
frozen lake really spin like a top?

11:32.990 --> 11:34.639
See, there is no string here.

11:34.640 --> 11:40.490
In other words, is this video the real
deal or is this myth on thin ice?

11:41.170 --> 11:42.980
Look, I gotta say I got
my doubts about this one.

11:42.981 --> 11:46.259
Yeah, I know this looks pretty bizarre,
but I think it's worth testing.

11:46.260 --> 11:46.958
I agree.

11:46.959 --> 11:48.738
But where are we gonna
find a frozen lake bed?

11:48.739 --> 11:49.868
It's the middle of summer.

11:49.869 --> 11:51.280
Yeah, I've been thinking about that.

11:51.281 --> 11:54.279
And I think we've gotta
build our own frozen lake.

11:54.280 --> 11:56.099
We've done crazier.

11:56.100 --> 11:58.240
Yeah, we should definitely
try two different shots.

11:58.360 --> 12:01.979
Maybe we shoot one directly into the
ice, and then one as a ricochet

12:01.980 --> 12:03.798
and see if one of those
gives us a spinning bullet.

12:03.799 --> 12:04.870
Okay, let's do it.

12:06.150 --> 12:07.930
But before anyone spins out,

12:08.520 --> 12:11.850
Tory's getting to grips with
a gun-grip, or ransom rest,

12:11.920 --> 12:14.700
because for this myth, geometry is key.

12:16.050 --> 12:19.779
Now if this myth is true, the
key element here is finding out

12:19.780 --> 12:21.859
which angle to fire the gun into the ice.

12:21.860 --> 12:24.730
So I have my gun, I have my ransom rest.

12:24.860 --> 12:27.250
Now what I need to do is
build a holder that is

12:27.360 --> 12:30.270
adjustable so we can fire at
the ice at different angles.

12:30.850 --> 12:33.139
Finding the right angle is vital.

12:33.140 --> 12:36.719
Too straight and the bullet
will deform, and not spin.

12:36.720 --> 12:41.590
Too shallow, and the slug will skip
off the ice and be lost forever.

12:42.010 --> 12:44.730
Now, I found out a little bit more
about the shooter in the myth.

12:44.820 --> 12:48.619
He was about six feet tall, and shot
about six feet in front of him.

12:48.620 --> 12:50.279
So since Tory is six feet tall,

12:50.280 --> 12:51.998
I'm going to have him stand
in for the shooter...

12:51.999 --> 12:53.760
Okay, Tory, put your
feet right at the line.

12:54.900 --> 12:57.340
...and have him hold
the gun and aim at six feet.

12:57.460 --> 13:00.619
Here is a laser pointer to help
you find the six foot mark.

13:00.620 --> 13:02.749
Then I'm going to check
the angle of the gun,

13:02.750 --> 13:04.440
and the distance it is from the ground.

13:04.441 --> 13:07.129
Okay, that is about 42 degrees.

13:07.130 --> 13:09.589
And let's see what the height is...

13:09.590 --> 13:12.619
about 44 1/2 inches.

13:12.620 --> 13:15.499
With that information, we can put
our ransom rest in the right place

13:15.500 --> 13:16.988
to get the results we are looking for.

13:16.989 --> 13:18.918
Now, we know where to set the ransom rest.

13:18.919 --> 13:20.090
- Well, at least where to start.
- Yeah.

13:20.930 --> 13:23.439
Knowing where to start is a start.

13:23.440 --> 13:25.509
And with a shooting rig ready to fire,

13:25.510 --> 13:27.610
they are off to take aim at this myth.

13:29.000 --> 13:31.029
We are on the rifle range
at Chabot Gun Club,

13:31.030 --> 13:34.840
so we can recreate the circumstances
of the spinning ice bullet.

13:35.320 --> 13:37.340
In the myth, this event takes place

13:37.350 --> 13:39.769
on a frozen pond in the middle of winter.

13:39.770 --> 13:43.869
But because it's the middle of summer
and we're in Northern California,

13:43.870 --> 13:47.119
frozen ponds are not in plentiful supply.

13:47.120 --> 13:48.270
All right, bring in the ice.

13:48.271 --> 13:51.519
But what we're going to
do is create our own,

13:51.520 --> 13:57.399
using nine forty inch by twenty-four
inch by ten inch thick solid ice blocks.

13:57.400 --> 13:58.610
Okay, there we go.

13:58.611 --> 14:00.010
"MythBusters" on ice.

14:01.140 --> 14:02.449
All right, maybe not.

14:02.450 --> 14:05.619
Putting those all together, and hopefully

14:05.620 --> 14:08.639
that amount of mass will be
enough to create a spin.

14:08.640 --> 14:11.309
It's certainly a large slice of ice,

14:11.310 --> 14:14.020
and the next best thing to a frozen lake.

14:14.470 --> 14:16.680
Is it bad if you can't
feel your fingertips?

14:17.100 --> 14:19.050
They said this would be a cool myth.

14:19.200 --> 14:20.560
I didn't believe them.

14:21.790 --> 14:24.560
Look at that, instant frozen lake.

14:24.690 --> 14:27.120
- I wouldn't say instant.
- Good point.

14:27.230 --> 14:30.020
So you'll notice that
we've set up a frozen lake

14:30.030 --> 14:31.890
with a smaller ice cube in front of it.

14:31.891 --> 14:34.109
Now that's because if you watch the video,

14:34.110 --> 14:37.469
it's hard to tell if the bullet
spins on the direct hit on the ice

14:37.470 --> 14:38.820
or via ricochet.

14:38.990 --> 14:42.089
In other words, does it hit and spin,

14:42.090 --> 14:44.570
or does it hit, bounce, land
somewhere else, and then spin.

14:44.571 --> 14:47.580
Well, in search of said spin,

14:47.720 --> 14:50.490
the team is first going for
the direct hit approach,

14:50.610 --> 14:53.560
firing straight into the
ice cube with this...

14:53.900 --> 14:56.629
What I have here is a Glock 9 millimeter.

14:56.630 --> 14:59.669
Now this is the gun
apparently used in the myth.

14:59.670 --> 15:01.080
We are about to fire a bullet

15:01.081 --> 15:04.279
into the ice to see if it'll
actually spin like a top.

15:04.280 --> 15:06.589
I can't wait to see what happens.

15:06.590 --> 15:10.950
The Glock is positioned in Tori's
angle finder to 42 degrees

15:11.150 --> 15:13.220
and then it's go time.

15:13.370 --> 15:15.669
Okay, so, we are gonna fire,

15:15.670 --> 15:19.269
and then look and listen for
any sort of spinning bullet.

15:19.270 --> 15:22.469
All right, this is spinning
bullet at 42 degrees.

15:22.470 --> 15:25.380
In three, two, one...

15:27.850 --> 15:29.119
The gun fires.

15:29.120 --> 15:30.130
The ice shatters.

15:30.300 --> 15:32.140
But what happens to the bullet?

15:32.290 --> 15:35.360
Well, we hit the ice, but
no spinning bullet.

15:35.500 --> 15:36.860
Look how much it fractured!

15:36.980 --> 15:38.190
I bet it's right in there.

15:38.760 --> 15:40.300
Kari is spot on.

15:40.460 --> 15:44.489
The bullet hit the ice and simply
embedded itself deep inside,

15:44.490 --> 15:46.650
where a spin is out of the question.

15:47.480 --> 15:51.410
But undeterred, the MythBusters
decide to try again.

15:52.700 --> 15:54.040
All right. The gun is loaded. We're hot.

15:54.041 --> 15:55.299
Let's do this.

15:55.300 --> 15:58.820
Round two, three, two, one...

16:02.800 --> 16:05.060
It's another 42 degree hit...

16:06.530 --> 16:07.790
...but with the same result.

16:08.450 --> 16:10.320
I don't see any spinning bullets.

16:11.080 --> 16:12.810
But all is not lost.

16:13.230 --> 16:14.919
Ok, we are 0 for 2.

16:14.920 --> 16:16.220
But you know what? That is fine.

16:16.221 --> 16:18.839
Because it doesn't always
work in the viral video.

16:18.840 --> 16:21.329
Not every shot yields a spin.

16:21.330 --> 16:23.330
So we can't call it just yet.

16:24.090 --> 16:26.770
In three, two, one...

16:27.390 --> 16:30.930
Test three also has nothing akin to a spin.

16:31.620 --> 16:36.589
But when they recover the round, there
is cause for cautious optimism.

16:36.590 --> 16:37.560
Oh, my gosh.

16:37.700 --> 16:38.820
Look at this.

16:39.490 --> 16:42.010
The bullet has not deformed,

16:42.170 --> 16:44.300
which means there might
be some truth to this myth.

16:44.410 --> 16:46.180
That could potentially spin.

16:46.310 --> 16:47.800
But with test four...

16:47.825 --> 16:50.969
Where is the elusive spinning bullet?

16:51.370 --> 16:52.570
...five,...

16:52.595 --> 16:53.795
It's not here.

16:54.410 --> 17:00.750
...six and seven also failing to spin
out, that optimism soon melts away.

17:00.930 --> 17:02.050
The sun is coming out.

17:02.200 --> 17:06.950
The lake is melting,
still no spinning bullet.

17:07.109 --> 17:09.690
Meaning it's time for a plan "B".

17:10.160 --> 17:13.329
So the direct hit experiment
isn't really giving us anything.

17:13.329 --> 17:16.550
So we're going to change our firing
angle and try for the ricochet.

17:16.720 --> 17:18.690
We are going to fire into the ice block

17:18.691 --> 17:21.419
and hope to catch a spinning
bullet on a larger frozen lake.

17:21.420 --> 17:23.209
This is not going to be easy.

17:23.210 --> 17:26.409
Coming right up
in "Spy car - the revenge"...

17:26.410 --> 17:28.890
I think that would hurt another
car if you drove into it.

17:28.891 --> 17:31.659
...will Jamie be psyched by his spike?

17:31.660 --> 17:32.830
The slasher.

17:33.010 --> 17:36.570
In three, two, one...

17:43.700 --> 17:48.030
So far in the spy spike department,
we tested the Goldfinger spike...

17:51.110 --> 17:53.750
...which did this kind of damage.

17:55.880 --> 17:59.799
We have also tested
the Green Hornet spike...

17:59.800 --> 18:00.690
Oh, crap.

18:01.710 --> 18:03.940
...which did this kind of damage.

18:05.900 --> 18:11.180
Now, apparently, Jamie has rigged up
some kind of special Hyneman sauce

18:11.320 --> 18:13.260
to come at me with one last time.

18:13.370 --> 18:16.380
Even though Adam was
psyched by the spikes...

18:16.405 --> 18:17.489
I'm going home.

18:17.490 --> 18:19.730
...Jamie saw room for improvement.

18:20.570 --> 18:23.160
I don't think he's gonna make it very far.

18:23.270 --> 18:27.660
So he slipped back to the shop to
conjure up a wheel of misfortune

18:29.150 --> 18:31.990
straight from the Hyneman House of Horrors.

18:33.330 --> 18:35.660
I think that'd hurt another
car if you drove into it.

18:36.380 --> 18:40.179
And back at the runway,
with nuts tightened,

18:40.180 --> 18:42.090
it's time to put it to the test.

18:42.680 --> 18:45.150
This design is about the worst
thing I could come up with.

18:45.151 --> 18:47.559
What's different about it is that

18:47.560 --> 18:50.929
the other designs all had
relatively long skinny shafts

18:50.930 --> 18:52.360
with a cutting blade on the tip.

18:52.361 --> 18:54.719
And those shafts could bend.

18:54.720 --> 18:57.819
The little blades around the tip could also

18:57.820 --> 18:59.860
bend or go relatively easily, and they did.

19:00.020 --> 19:06.020
Whereas this has this massive
base, that's very strong,

19:06.160 --> 19:10.479
so I reckon this will go right into
the car and just keep on cutting

19:10.480 --> 19:12.319
without damaging itself.

19:12.320 --> 19:13.850
- Are you ready?
- I am.

19:13.980 --> 19:19.720
Okay, the slasher, in three, two, one...

19:21.850 --> 19:25.250
For the final time, the MythBusters
motor down the runway,

19:27.390 --> 19:31.200
until the red flag signals
the bullish Jamie to charge.

19:35.300 --> 19:37.990
Straight away, he takes
out Adam's rear tire.

19:40.610 --> 19:43.600
Then he slices and dices
along the whole side.

19:46.910 --> 19:48.440
Come on, Jamie, I can take more!

19:49.760 --> 19:53.360
With Adam at his mercy,
Jamie goes in for the kill.

19:55.650 --> 19:57.029
Not enough for you?

19:57.030 --> 20:00.579
...and rips the entire
front tire clean off...

20:00.580 --> 20:02.230
Had enough?

20:03.290 --> 20:05.860
...leaving only one possible outcome.

20:06.440 --> 20:08.800
That was too much fun.

20:10.730 --> 20:14.370
That fulfills like a deep
childhood fantasy.

20:14.740 --> 20:16.329
I want another car.

20:16.330 --> 20:17.720
I want to do this again.

20:18.170 --> 20:22.159
It was a heavy metal massacre in
the truest sense of the word.

20:22.160 --> 20:23.390
I got to see this.

20:26.180 --> 20:28.190
I think I messed your car up a little bit.

20:30.230 --> 20:31.560
I'm sorry about that.

20:32.320 --> 20:34.039
I don't know what I was thinking.

20:34.040 --> 20:37.420
That is a horror sight.

20:37.660 --> 20:39.180
Where's my tire?

20:39.330 --> 20:41.210
My tire... is not... oh, there it is!

20:41.235 --> 20:43.035
I'd say my spike was pretty effective.

20:43.040 --> 20:44.618
I mean there is not a whole lot more

20:44.619 --> 20:46.870
that you can do to the side of a car.

20:46.920 --> 20:51.050
Not only did I pop the tires,
but I completely removed them.

20:51.750 --> 20:54.080
The car can't move at all now,

20:54.210 --> 20:57.120
because the chassis is sitting
on the ground in fact.

20:58.660 --> 21:00.780
It worked a little better
than I thought it would.

21:01.780 --> 21:04.620
With spy myth one a slashing success,

21:04.770 --> 21:07.560
it's time to bring out the big guns.

21:12.690 --> 21:15.590
Is this firearm's film the real deal,

21:16.810 --> 21:18.480
or just bullet baloney?

21:18.680 --> 21:21.630
Can a slug really spin like a frozen top?

21:22.610 --> 21:24.690
Three, two, one...

21:25.070 --> 21:28.720
Well, the MythBusters direct
hit approach was shot down.

21:29.010 --> 21:30.990
I don't see any spinning bullet.

21:31.360 --> 21:33.470
So it's time to modify the method.

21:34.510 --> 21:36.930
So far, the direct shot did not work.

21:37.110 --> 21:39.060
So we are going to move on to the ricochet,

21:39.240 --> 21:42.130
which brings into play our
larger frozen lake bed.

21:42.310 --> 21:44.390
What we are going to do is lower
the angle of the shot,

21:44.480 --> 21:48.530
hopefully allowing the bullet to skip off
the ice on to our frozen lake bed,

21:48.570 --> 21:50.680
and we'll see if we can
get that bullet spinning.

21:50.900 --> 21:55.210
We actually have information from
the guy who supposedly did this.

21:55.500 --> 22:00.060
What he told us is that every time
he tried it, the bullet landed between

22:00.250 --> 22:03.840
two and eight feet from the
point of impact with the ice.

22:04.320 --> 22:08.750
We have a ten foot slab of ice out there.

22:08.950 --> 22:10.160
Sounds easy?

22:10.400 --> 22:11.600
It won't be.

22:12.120 --> 22:13.800
Well, to find out, they are starting

22:14.000 --> 22:17.270
by using a ricochet-friendly
angle of 30 degrees.

22:18.000 --> 22:19.100
Hoping this works.

22:19.320 --> 22:22.160
In three, two, one...

22:23.450 --> 22:24.690
It's a clean hit.

22:24.900 --> 22:26.490
But the bullet's gone AWOL.

22:26.670 --> 22:29.450
It's not on the pond, nor in the cube.

22:30.080 --> 22:31.190
Wait a minute, that's good news,

22:31.380 --> 22:32.320
cause the bullet isn't in there.

22:32.530 --> 22:33.650
It did ricochet, I don't
know where it went,

22:33.651 --> 22:35.460
but at least it popped out.

22:35.550 --> 22:36.600
Right.

22:36.910 --> 22:41.080
The high speed confirms that on the
one hand, they did get a ricochet.

22:41.480 --> 22:45.330
But on the other, the bouncing
bullet did not land on their lake.

22:46.590 --> 22:48.900
So, they reset for try two.

22:49.110 --> 22:51.370
All right, let's go before spring comes.

22:53.870 --> 22:56.050
But again, the bullet disappears.

22:57.110 --> 22:59.180
The good news is, we got a ricochet.

22:59.410 --> 23:01.750
The bad news, we can't
find the bullet anywhere.

23:01.950 --> 23:03.340
It's nowhere on the lake bed.

23:03.420 --> 23:05.080
So that's why we have this.

23:05.260 --> 23:07.620
This back board with the white
paper is going to tell us.

23:07.830 --> 23:10.670
If the bullet hits this, we'll
know exactly where it goes.

23:11.470 --> 23:12.100
Alright, we are hot.

23:12.101 --> 23:13.620
That's the theory.

23:13.630 --> 23:14.960
Is this the magic formula?

23:15.150 --> 23:15.970
But in practice...

23:15.995 --> 23:17.195
One!

23:17.800 --> 23:21.160
...even the ricochet catcher
doesn't catch the ricochet.

23:21.380 --> 23:25.120
So it must be firing way
over our back board.

23:25.550 --> 23:28.040
So next, the team wrangles the angle.

23:28.310 --> 23:30.679
But where it be high...

23:30.680 --> 23:33.060
- Alright, we are loaded in 45 degrees.
- One!

23:34.540 --> 23:35.419
...low...

23:35.420 --> 23:36.310
31 degrees.

23:37.000 --> 23:38.509
...or somewhere in between,...

23:38.510 --> 23:41.130
All right, we are locked and loaded
at a 38-degree angle.

23:42.210 --> 23:45.369
...the ricocheting round
never lands on the lake.

23:45.370 --> 23:48.540
And... I don't see a spinning bullet.

23:48.690 --> 23:50.110
I don't see the ricochet at all.

23:50.310 --> 23:52.640
- Anything?
- The back board is clean.

23:52.930 --> 23:54.580
You know, we can be here all day.

23:54.870 --> 23:56.470
We have been here all day.

23:56.850 --> 23:58.690
And what a frustrating day it's been.

23:59.050 --> 24:01.410
But without finding a single ricochet,

24:01.620 --> 24:05.040
it's just not possible to call
the myth one way or the other.

24:05.880 --> 24:08.630
We have been experimenting all day
to find the perfect conditions

24:08.800 --> 24:10.930
to create the mythical spinning bullet.

24:11.110 --> 24:14.020
Now we have the right temperature
of ice, the right hardness.

24:14.090 --> 24:17.480
Unfortunately, we have an
extremely unpredictable ricochet.

24:17.660 --> 24:19.680
We can't find where the bullet lands.

24:20.210 --> 24:22.110
Now, we've created the biggest frozen pond

24:22.111 --> 24:24.429
that we possibly could in summer with

24:24.430 --> 24:26.760
all of the available ice
that we could source.

24:27.200 --> 24:28.360
We need to go bigger.

24:28.560 --> 24:31.780
We need something a little more
naturally huge and frozen.

